## 5. Mandatory Remote Repository Provisioning (The Parity Rule)

**This is a hard rule.** A local `git init` without first creating the repository on GitHub produces zero remote parity — the repo appears healthy locally but is invisible on GitHub. This is exactly the failure mode that caused `T1-vrvish-profile` to be missing for weeks.

**The Rule:**  
When any agent scaffolds a new platform or repository for the first time, it MUST provision the remote GitHub repository via **`Engine_Git_SourceControl.js`** before the first push. Do NOT use raw `git` CLI commands or raw PowerShell `curl` for this — use the engine.

### Canonical Usage:
```js
const Engine_Git_SourceControl = require('C:/GitHub/T1-vrvish-core/scripts/T0-Core/engines/Engine_Git_SourceControl');
const engine = new Engine_Git_SourceControl('C:/GitHub/MY-REPO-NAME');

// 1. Provision the remote repo on GitHub (uses GITHUB_PAT from .env)
await engine.createRemoteRepo('MY-REPO-NAME', { private: true });

// 2. Sync all local changes up
await engine.sync('feat(init): initial scaffold');
```

`createRemoteRepo()` calls the GitHub REST API (`POST /user/repos`) internally, stores the PAT from `.env`, and sets the remote origin automatically.

> [!CAUTION]
> Never assume a remote repo exists just because a `git remote -v` shows an origin URL. Always call `createRemoteRepo()` on first scaffold.